,"1315":"1315","1414":"1414","1402":"1402","1401":"1401","1312":"1312","about 1339":"circa 1339","November 1379":"november 1379","1375":"1375","1342":"1342","about 1395":"circa 1395","1449":"1449","1339":"1339","Church Barham, Barham, Kent, England":"Barham, Kent, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk","England":"England","Kent, England":"Kent, England","Barham, Kent, England":"Barham, Kent, England","Digges Court, Barnham, Kent, England":"Kent, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk"},"en":{"about 1339– after 1402":"about 1339–after 1402","1339–1402":"1339–1402","1342–1414":"1342–1414","1362–1401":"1362–1401","1385–1449":"1385–1449","1385–Female":"1385–Deceased","–Female":"Deceased","1312–1375":"1312–1375","1315–1395":"1315–1395"," after 1402":"after 1402","1385":"1385","1362":"1362","1395":"1395","1382":"1382","1315":"1315","1414":"1414","1402":"1402","1401":"1401","1312":"1312","about 1339":"about 1339","November 1379":"November 1379","1375":"1375","1342":"1342","about 1395":"about 1395","1449":"1449","1339":"1339","Church Barham, Barham, Kent, England":"Barham, Kent, England, United Kingdom","England":"England","Kent, England":"Kent, England","Barham, Kent, England":"Barham, Kent, England","Digges Court, Barnham, Kent, England":"Kent, England, United Kingdom","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Digges","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English (Wiltshire):","variant of   Dicks  , from the personal name <i>Digge</i>, a variant of   Dick   with voicing of the final consonant.","alternatively, a nickname from Middle English <i>digge</i> ‘duck’, with post-medieval excrescent <i>-s</i>, probably applied as a metonymic occupational name for someone who kept, caught, or sold ducks or for someone thought to resemble a duck in some way."],"variants":[{"name":"Diggs","meanings":["English (London): variant of   Digges  . This form of the surname is now rare in Britain."]},{"name":"Dicks","meanings":["English: variant of   Dick  , with genitival or post-medieval excrescent <i>-s</i>.","English: variant of   Dykes  .","North German and Dutch: genitive patronymic from the personal name   Dick  . In North America, this surname may also be an altered form of the much more common Dutch variant <b>Diks</b>."]}]},{"name":"John","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Contracted form of Old French <i>Jo(h)anne</i>, from Latin <i>Io(h)anna</i> (  see  Joanna  ). In England this was the usual feminine form of   John   from the Middle English period onwards and was extremely popular, but in the 16th and 17th centuries it steadily lost ground to   Jane .  It was strongly revived in the first part of the 20th century, partly under the influence of  George Bernard Shaw's  play St Joan (  1923 ), based on the life of  Joan of Arc  (  1412–31 ). Claiming to be guided by the voices of the saints, she persuaded the French dauphin to defy the occupying English forces and have himself crowned, and she led the French army that raised the siege of Orleans in  1429 . The following year she was captured by the Burgundians and sold to the English, and a year later she was burned at the stake for witchcraft at the age of 18 or 19. Her story has captured the imagination of many writers, and she is variously portrayed as a national and political hero, a model of apolitical straightforwardness and honesty, and a religious heroine. She was canonized in  1920 . More recent influences have included the American film actress  Joan Crawford  (  1908–77 , born  Lucille le Sueur ), the British actress  Joan Collins  (  b. 1933 ), the American comedienne  Joan Rivers  (  b. 1933 ), and the West Indian pop singer  Joan Armatrading  (  b. 1950 )."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705195,"age":43,"year":"1382","julianDay":2225826,"title":"Wycliffe's Bible","description":"John Wycliffe, English theologian and professor at the University of Oxford, completed a translation of the Bible from the Latin Vulgate into Middle English. This translation is known as Wycliffe's Bible and was completed around 1382.","url":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Wycliffe%27s_Bible","urlTitle":"Wikipedia - Wycliffe's Bible","jurisdictionLevel":1}],"lifeSummary":"When John Digges was born about 1339, in Kent, England, his father, Roger Digges, was 29 and his mother, Albina Northwode, was 26. He married Juliana Northwood in November 1379. They were the parents of at least 1 son and 4 daughters. He died after 1402, in England."},"et":{"about 1339– after 1402":"umbes 1339–pärast 1402","1339–1402":"1339–1402","1342–1414":"1342–1414","1362–1401":"1362–1401","1385–1449":"1385–1449","1385–Female":"1385–Surnud","–Female":"Surnud","1312–1375":"1312–1375","1315–1395":"1315–1395"," after 1402":"pärast 1402","1385":"1385","1362":"1362","1395":"1395","1382":"1382","1315":"1315","1414":"1414","1402":"1402","1401":"1401","1312":"1312","about 1339":"umbes 1339","November 1379":"november 1379","1375":"1375","1342":"1342","about 1395":"umbes 1395","1449":"1449","1339":"1339","Church Barham, Barham, Kent, England":"Barham, Kent, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","England":"England","Kent, England":"Kent, England","Barham, Kent, England":"Barham, Kent, England","Digges Court, Barnham, Kent, England":"Kent, Inglismaa, United Kingdom"},"fi":{"about 1339– after 1402":"noin 1339–1402 jälkeen","1339–1402":"1339–1402","1342–1414":"1342–1414","1362–1401":"1362–1401","1385–1449":"1385–1449","1385–Female":"1385–Kuollut","–Female":"Kuollut","1312–1375":"1312–1375","1315–1395":"1315–1395"," after 1402":"1402 jälkeen","1385":"1385","1362":"1362","1395":"1395","1382":"1382","1315":"1315","1414":"1414","1402":"1402","1401":"1401","1312":"1312","about 1339":"noin 1339","November 1379":"marraskuu 1379","1375":"1375","1342":"1342","about 1395":"noin 1395","1449":"1449","1339":"1339","Church Barham, Barham, Kent, England":"Barham, Kent, Englanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta